AUDIO: 'When powered by Hollow 1, Surfer H achieves a 92.2% 2% state-of-the-art performance on Web Voyager, striking a paro optimal balance between accuracy and cost efficiency. The good thing'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about these models is they\'re small and efficient. And these are models that you can take, you can build stuff on top of, and they work really well. And each company also released their own benchmark open-source as well that is'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called the webclick evaluation data set. So, first, why browser use agents? Why computer use agents? Why are these things important? Well, they talk about it here. However, there they are being agents, real world utility remains'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bounded by the available predefined tools and the engineering effort required to expand them. We live in a world in which the internet is built for humans mostly. And so the companies offering products and services on the'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'internet don\'t always have well doumented and standardized APIs for agents to interact with. And so in that sense, we need web agents to interact with the website in the same way that humans interact with the website by'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clicking, scrolling, highlighting, all the stuff that we do as humans with a website. Computer use agents have recently emerged as a new paradigm in which agents interact with software directly through graphical user interfaces. This approach avoids relying'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on custom integrations or APIs. And this is where they present Surfer H, a visual web retrieval agent designed to be easily trained through reinforcement learning techniques. Surfer H comprises three main modules, a policy, a'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'localizer, and a validator. These modules are compatible with any VLM capable of proposing and evaluating actions. Any VLM, vision language model. Our agent only uses screenshots from'

[05:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'websites and does not require the document object model or the accessibility tree of the website. So it doesn\'t actually need to see the code. It just simply takes a screenshot, figures out what\'s on it, and then'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'figures out the coordinates of the right button to click on. Hollow one is a family of lightweight VLM specializing in taking and evaluating actions and localizing UI elements. Localizing means figuring out where to click. All right, so how does it actually work? So as'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mentioned, there are three pieces. The policy, the localizer, and a validator. The policy proposes actions that are executed sequentially. So that is go to the website, scroll down, click this button, etc. Then web actions are'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'executed in a browser by simulating human-like interactions. If the policy generates an action that requires interacting with a specific element on a web page, such as a like button, it generates a textual description of the'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'element and the localizer provides its 2D coordinates. Then when the policy emits an answer, it is passed through a validator. The validator generates feedback about the answer and decides whether it is suitable for the user. If'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the answer is valid, it is returned to the user. Great, it figured it out. It solved the task. Otherwise, the feedback is incorporated into the agent\'s memory and the agent continues its execution'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'until either completion or reaching a time or cost budget. So, here\'s what that flow looks like. We give it a task. It comes in. It stores the task in memory. Then, it creates a policy, the list of steps. Here\'s what that looks'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like. Refresh. Go to the URL. Go back. Scroll. Wait. Right. Click. Now, these XY coordinates in red are produced by the localizer. It looks at the screenshot and figures out where to click on the screen. Now, the answer'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'goes to the validator. If the validator says, "Nope, that\'s not quite right." It goes back, provides that feedback, stores it in memory, and then does it again. If it needs to continue using the browser, it does so, and then eventually the validator checks, hey, is the'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'overall task completed? And if so, gives the quote unquote answer. basically what you asked for the task completion. So let\'s look at some benchmarks. This is the click accuracy across models and benchmarks. So on the left we have a'

